2.3 Vendor (Vendor App — cross-platform)
•
FR-V1: Vendor downloads app and registers providing: store name, store address, pin code, store map location (geolocation pin), contact person, phone, email, business hours, and documents for verification (GST, ID, bank proof).
•
FR-V2: Admin must moderate (approve) vendor registration before vendor becomes active.
•
FR-V3: Vendors see incoming orders from customers that are within their configured proximity/radius and within service time. Orders should show estimated route distance, delivery time, and order details.
•
FR-V4: Race condition rule: The first vendor to accept the order becomes assigned and the order disappears from other vendors’ lists immediately.
•
FR-V5: Vendors can accept/reject orders. If accepted, vendor must confirm dispatch and mark delivery milestones (picked up, en route, delivered).
•
FR-V6: Vendors see only their own order history and performance metrics (orders served, success rate, revenue).
•
FR-V7: Vendors can chat with the assigned customer (in-app), update ETA, and add delivery notes.
•
FR-V8: Vendors must be able to update item availability and stock (if they manage their own stock).
•
FR-V9: Vendors receive push notifications for new orders, cancellations, messages, payouts.
•
FR-V10: Vendors see payout/invoice statements
•
FR-V11: Analytics for vendors to see weekly sales statements, insights, avg. customer ratings.
3. Key Business Rules & Workflows
3.1 Order lifecycle (typical)
1.
Customer places order (cart -> checkout -> payment).
2.
System records order and marks it Pending Assignment with geolocation of delivery address.
3.
System finds vendors within radius (configurable) who are active and available.
Auto-parts Marketplace & Vendor Dispatch App
Document Vesion: v1.1
DeepCognix AI Labs Pvt. Ltd., CIN: U72100KA2025PTC203794 (DPIIT / MSME Certified)
www.DeepCognix.com | deepcognix@gmail.com | 080-42041893
4.
System pushes real-time order notification to nearby vendors (queue).
5.
First Accept Wins: vendor presses Accept — system applies atomic lock (Redis or DB transaction) to set vendor_id on order. Order removed from other vendor queues.
6.
Vendor dispatches and updates status (Dispatched, Delivered). Customer and admin notified.
7.
Admin can reassign if vendor fails to dispatch within timeline or cancels.
3.2 Vendor Proximity & Assignment Rules
•
Proximity radius configurable (km). Option: prefer vendors with faster average service time or higher rating.
•
If no vendor accepts within X minutes, escalate to admin for manual assignment, or broaden radius.
•
Admin override allowed.
3.3 Payment & Settlement
•
Payments processed via Payment Gateway. Gateway webhooks notify app backend of success/failure.
•
Admin receives payments into platform merchant account. If vendor payouts are required, platform records payable to vendor and triggers periodic payouts (manual or scheduled).
•
Refunds managed in admin console (full or partial). Refund flow must reverse payment with gateway API and mark order refunded.
4. Non-Functional Requirements (NFRs)
•
NFR-1 (Cross-Platform): Single codebase preferred. Support iOS, Android, Windows desktop.
•
NFR-2 (Lightweight): App install size minimal and efficient runtime memory usage.
•
NFR-3 (Centralized DB): Single central database (Postgres recommended) hosted in cloud (AWS/Azure/GCP).
•
NFR-4 (Realtime): Real-time features (order push & chat) via WebSocket (socket.io) or Firebase Realtime / FCM for notifications.
•
NFR-5 (Performance): API response < 300ms typical for catalog queries; scale to thousands of daily active users with horizontal scaling.
•
NFR-6 (Availability): 99.9% uptime SLA for core services.
