Payment card data: rely on gateway & do not store sensitive card data unless PCI scope is handled.
12. Monitoring & Observability
•
App + API logging (structured logs). Centralized logging (ELK or Cloud equivalent).
•
Alerting on failures, payment webhook failures, database errors.
13. Backup & Disaster Recovery
•
Daily DB backups; point-in-time recovery (PITR).
•
Backup retention policy (e.g., 30/90 days).
14. Testing & QA
•
Unit tests for business logic.
•
API integration tests (orders & payment flows).
•
Load testing for peak order intake (simulate many vendors & customers).
•
UAT with sample vendors & customers.
15. Acceptance Criteria (examples)
•
AC1: A customer can register using mobile number with OTP and place an order; payment success results in order present in admin console and vendor queue.
•
AC2: When multiple vendors receive same order, only the first vendor to accept is assigned; other vendors no longer see the order within 2 seconds.
•
AC3: Admin can add categories and upload 1,000 items via CSV in batch and they appear in catalog within expected time.
•
AC4: Vendors see only orders assigned to them and their own order history.
•
AC5: Customers can chat with assigned vendor and receive replies in realtime.
16. Suggested Tech Stack & Services (recommendations)
•
Frontend mobile: Flutter (single codebase, supports iOS/Android/Windows desktop). Alternative: React Native + React Native Windows (less mature Windows support).
